      <li class="ctsh clearfix" data-cid="34652283">
        <div class="ilst">
          <a href="https://www.douban.com/people/2772645/"><img src="https://img3.doubanio.com/icon/u2772645-5.jpg" alt="白菜" class="" /></a>
        </div>
        <div class="con">
          <div class="nlst">
            <h3>
              <div class="note-toggle rr">
                <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/34652283/" class="note-unfolder">展开</a>
                <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="note-folder">收起</a>
              </div>
              <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/34652283/" class="">第334页</a></h3>
          </div>
          <div class="clst">
            <p class="user"><a href="https://www.douban.com/people/2772645/" class=" " title="白菜">白菜</a>
              
            </p>
            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="34652283">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">
. *Sophists* were professional teachers of fifth-century B.C.E. Greece whose attack on traditional moral values marks the beginnings of ethical philosophy. 259 
*智者学派 (Sophists)* 活跃于公元前15世纪的古希腊职业教师。他们攻击传统道德价值，这标志着伦理哲学的开始。
. *Socrates* sought to discover the essences of moral virtues and championed the use of reason in moral deliberation. 259 
*苏格..</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2015-03-25 14:32</span>
                  
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                
. *Sophists* were professional teachers of fifth-century B.C.E. Greece whose attack on traditional moral values marks the beginnings of ethical philosophy. 259 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*智者学派 (Sophists)* 活跃于公元前15世纪的古希腊职业教师。他们攻击传统道德价值，这标志着伦理哲学的开始。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Socrates* sought to discover the essences of moral virtues and championed the use of reason in moral deliberation. 259 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*苏格拉底 (Socrates，约前470一前399)* 他试图揭示德性的本质，主张用理性思辨来审视道德问题。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Plato* also sought the essences of moral virtues, identifying these with the unchanging Forms, the highest of which he held to be the Form of the Good, the ultimate source of all value and reality. 259 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*柏拉图 (Plato)* 他也在寻求德性的本质。它把德性的本质归结为永恒不变的理念，而最高的理念则是至善之理念，它是一切价值和真实性的终极源泉。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Aesara of Lucania* was a Pythagorean philosopher from southern Italy who held that, <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>by introspecting about the nature and structure of the human soul, we can identify a standard of personal and public morality. 263 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*卢卡尼亚人爱莎若 (Aesara of Lucania 公元前350年左右)* 她来自意大利南部，是毕达哥拉斯派的哲学家。她主张，通过反省人类灵魂的本性和结构，我们就能确定一个个人和公共道德的标准。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Aristotle* was an ethical naturalist who held that moral judgments are judgments of fact about the natural world. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>He said that happiness is our highest good. 264 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*亚里士多德  (Aristotle)* 是一位伦理学自然主义者，他主张道德判断就是关于自然世界的事实判断。他说幸福就是最高的善。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Epicurus*, an ethical egoist, held that one's highest objective is to lead the pleasant life through moderate living. 267 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*伊壁鸠鲁 (Epicurus，前341一前270)* 一位伦理学利己主义者，主张人的最高目标就是以温和节制的生活方式度过一个快乐的人生。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Zeno* was the founder of Stoicism. 267 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*芝诺 (Zeno，前334～前262)* 斯多葛主义创始人。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Epictetus*, a leading Stoic, held that one's highest objective is to find a serene or untroubled life through acceptance of the rational natural order of things. 268 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*爱比克泰德 (Epictetus，60一117)* 一位主要的斯多葛主义者。主张人的最高目标就是通过接受事物的合乎理性的自然秩序来获取一种宁静超然的人生。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Diogenes* was the most famous Cynic, who taught by shocking example that the wise person reduces all wants and avoids all comforts. 269 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*第欧根尼 （Diogenes 公元前4世纪）* 一位著名的犬儒，他用令人吃惊的方式告诉大家，智慧的人应当减少一切需求，并拒绝一切使生活便利的外部条件。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *St. Augustine* used Platonic concepts to solve “the problem of evil,” <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>held moral evil to be misdirected love, <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>and identified God as the supreme moral authority and source of all goodness. 270 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*圣奥古斯丁 (St. Augustine 354—430)* 他用柏拉图主义的概念解决“恶的问题”，主张道德上的恶就是扭曲的爱。它把上帝定义为最高的道德权威和一切善的源泉。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *St. Hildegard of Bingen* was a medieval German mystic philosopher who held that the moral powers of the soul come from its three faculties: understanding, insight, and execution. 272 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*宾根的圣希德嘉 (St. Hildegard of Bingen 生于11世纪末)* 是中世纪德国的神秘主义哲学家。她主张灵魂的道德力量来自它的三种能力：理解力，洞察力，还有实践力。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Heloise* was a medieval French philosopher who held that the morality or immorality of an action is determined by the intention with which it is done. 274 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*爱洛伊斯 (Heloise，1100一1163)* 是中世纪法国的哲学家，他主张行为的道德或非道德取决于行为施行时的意向。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*Peter Abelard* set forth one of medieval philosophy's most careful analyses of the morality of intent. 274 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*彼得.阿伯拉尔 (Peter Abelard，1079—1142)* 在中世纪的哲学家中，是他对意向的道德性作了最为仔细的分析。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *St.Thomas Aquinas* reconciled Aristotelian ethical naturalism with Christianity. 276 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*圣托马斯.阿奎那 (St.Thomas Aquinas)* 调和了亚里士多德的自然主义伦理学和基督教思想。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Thomas Hobbes* held that “good” and “evil” denote what a person desires or hates; he maintained that our natural end is preservation of self. 277 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*托马斯.霍布斯 (Hobbes 1588--1679)* 主张“善”和“恶”指的就是人们欲求或憎恶之物，他认为我们的自然目标就是保存自己。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *David Hume* held that moral principles are neither divine edicts nor discoverable by reason and that value judgments are based on emotion. He said that the act that pleases our moral sensibilities is one that re.ects the agent's benevolent character. 279 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*大卫.休谟 (Hume 1711—1776)* 主张道德原则既不是神圣命令，也不能用理性来揭示，价值判断的基础是情感。他认为我们取悦我们的道德感受力的行为反映的是当事人的仁爱性情。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Immanuel Kant* held that the supreme pre-scription of morality is to act always in such a way that you could rationally will the principle on which you act to be a universal law. He believed that what you should do, you should do, not because it promotes some end but simply because it is right. 281 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*伊曼努尔.康德 (Immanuel Kant，1724--1804)* 主张最高的道德命令就是：如此这般地行动，以便你能够合乎理性地让你据以行动的那条准则变成普遍法则。他认伪，你之所以应当做该做的事，并不是因为它能达到什么目的，而是因为它是正确的。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Jeremy Bentham*, a utilitarian, held that the rightness of an action is identical with the pleasure it produces as its consequence and said that pleasure can be evaluated quantitatively. 284 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*杰尼米.边沁 (Bentham)* 一位功利主义者，主张行为的正确性取决于它所产生的快乐。他还认为快乐可以定量地来衡量。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *John Stuart Mill*, a utilitarian, held that the rightness of an action is identical with the happiness that it produces as its consequence and said that pleasure -- a part of happiness --  must be measured in terms of quality as well as quantity. 284 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*约翰.斯图亚特.穆勒 (Mill)* 一位功利主义者，主张行为的正确性取决于它所产生的结果的幸福。他还认为快乐 -- 幸福的一部分 -- 不仅应该从量上来衡量，还应该从质上来评估。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>. *Friedrich Nietzsche* distinguished between slave morality (the morality of the masses) and master morality (the morality of the nobleman). The former represents the denial of life; the latter represents the will-to-power. 288 <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>*弗里德里希.尼采 (Friedrich Nietzsche 1844～1900)* 区分了奴隶道德（大多数人的道德）和主人道德（高贵者的道德）。前者代表了对生命的否定，而后者体现了权力意志。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>
                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







